---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';


const path = '/compare/yotpo-email-sms-vs-mailchimp';
const title = 'Yotpo Email & SMS vs Mailchimp for Shopify: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Yotpo Email & SMS vs Mailchimp for Shopify — reviews-loyalty suite lifecycle vs generalist email, graduation timing, and Shopify-native automation fit.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Yotpo Email & SMS or Mailchimp better for a Shopify store doing $35k/mo?',
    answer: 'Mailchimp wins early when you need affordable broadcasts and basic automations without suite complexity — adequate for simple catalogs under ~400 orders/month. Yotpo Email & SMS wins when Yotpo Reviews or Loyalty is live and post-purchase UGC drives repeat revenue. At $35k/mo without Yotpo modules, graduating to Omnisend or Klaviyo often beats Yotpo Email alone — Yotpo value requires Reviews infrastructure.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should I graduate from Mailchimp?',
    answer: 'Graduate when Shopify order sync, cart recovery sophistication, SMS needs, or post-purchase UGC timing outgrow Mailchimp\'s ecommerce depth — typically past 500 orders/month or $40k/mo for most catalogs. If Yotpo Reviews is live simultaneously, consider Yotpo Email & SMS instead of Mailchimp-to-Klaviyo path for suite consolidation.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Yotpo vs Mailchimp pricing compare at 10,000 contacts?',
    answer: 'Mailchimp at 10k contacts often runs $80–150/mo depending on send volume and plan tier. Yotpo Email & SMS pricing ties to broader Yotpo contract — standalone can exceed Mailchimp until Reviews and Loyalty modules justify bundle. Mailchimp looks cheaper for broadcast-heavy stores without UGC strategy; Yotpo looks cheaper when consolidating three Yotpo modules at renewal.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Mailchimp replace Yotpo Email & SMS while keeping Yotpo Reviews?',
    answer: 'Yes technically — Mailchimp sends lifecycle email while Yotpo owns review collection and display. You lose native review-request timing and loyalty earn integration Mailchimp cannot replicate without configuration. Many merchants outgrow Mailchimp before Yotpo Email makes sense; those on Yotpo Reviews at scale usually consolidate under Yotpo Email rather than downgrading to Mailchimp.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Yotpo or Mailchimp?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits when Mailchimp feels too shallow but Yotpo suite feels premature — guided lifecycle playbooks with pay-per-email pricing and unlimited contacts. Mailchimp still wins very early stage. Yotpo still wins when Reviews and Loyalty are live. Sequenzy helps merchants graduating Mailchimp without adopting full Yotpo suite or Klaviyo complexity.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better Shopify ecommerce automations?',
    answer: 'Yotpo Email & SMS when suite modules are active — post-purchase review requests, loyalty earn, and cart recovery enriched by UGC data. Mailchimp offers basic Shopify automations adequate for early stage but weaker cart recovery, SMS integration, and review-native sequencing. Neither matches Klaviyo predictive depth; both lose to Yotpo on integrated UGC when Reviews is live.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles post-purchase review requests better?',
    answer: 'Yotpo natively when Reviews module is active — fulfillment timing, photo prompts, reviewer segmentation without sync. Mailchimp has no review infrastructure — post-purchase is generic cross-sell at best. Merchants on Yotpo Reviews who stay Mailchimp-only for email leave review velocity and suite economics on the table.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Build welcome, cart, post-purchase review request if Reviews is live, and winback. Score time-to-live, review submission lift, and Shopify trigger reliability. If Yotpo Reviews is active, lean Yotpo Email. If under $30k/mo without UGC strategy, Mailchimp may still suffice — plan graduation before BFCM surprises you.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Yotpo Email & SMS vs Mailchimp</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="catalog-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Yotpo Email & SMS vs Mailchimp for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Suite trust loops versus generalist email familiarity. Yotpo Email & SMS optimizes lifecycle messaging when reviews and loyalty data should inform every send. Mailchimp optimizes for merchants who need affordable broadcasts and basic automations before ecommerce retention complexity justifies specialized tooling. We evaluated both through a $32k/mo artisan hot sauce brand still adequate on Mailchimp, a $58k/mo organic baby food label that graduated Mailchimp after Yotpo Reviews went live, and a $41k/mo gourmet chocolate shop that chose Mailchimp over Yotpo Email because Reviews was not in their stack.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Early stage simplicity', tool: 'Mailchimp', reason: 'Affordable broadcasts and basic automations.' },
            { label: 'Reviews + loyalty email', tool: 'Yotpo', reason: 'Native UGC timing and points earn sequences.' },
            { label: 'Suite consolidation', tool: 'Yotpo', reason: 'One vendor when Reviews or Loyalty already live.' },
            { label: 'Graduation path', tool: 'Mailchimp', reason: 'Fine until Shopify triggers and UGC outgrow it.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Guided playbooks when graduating Mailchimp without suite lock-in.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Yotpo Email & SMS</th><th>Mailchimp</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Reviews/loyalty suite merchants</td><td>Early-stage generalist email</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>Bundle-dependent pricing</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$13/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Yotpo contract tiers</td><td>Contacts + send volume</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify depth</td><td>Native + reviews/loyalty data</td><td>Basic integration</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Reviews integration</td><td>Native</td><td>None</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SMS</td><td>Built-in, suite-tied</td><td>Limited / add-on</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Automation depth</td><td>Full lifecycle + UGC</td><td>Basic journeys</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Learning curve</td><td>Moderate; suite context</td><td>Low for beginners</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>What this comparison is actually about</h2>
        <p>
          Yotpo Email & SMS and Mailchimp sit in the same Shopify email-tools category — newsletters, lifecycle automation, and transactional-style customer moments — but they punish different operational mistakes. Yotpo Email & SMS is optimized when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Mailchimp is optimized when broadcast muscle memory outweighs Shopify trigger depth. Buyers who choose on brand recognition alone often end up paying for depth they never open or speed they outgrow in ninety days.
        </p>
        <p>
          We tested both against specialty catalogs where retention is genuinely hard: vinyl scarcity, keyboard group buys, tea replenishment, climbing research cycles, pottery gifts, outdoor segmentation, board game allocation, coffee roast dates, and camping quiz capture. Those verticals stress education, suppression, and timing more honestly than generic one-size-fits-all demos. The writeup below is intentionally merchant-specific — not a feature matrix dressed in adjectives.
        </p>
        <h2>How outdoor gear retailer emails through Memorial Day sale week</h2>
        <p>
          The outdoor gear retailer does 2,400 orders/mo at roughly $112k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows layering guides and ultralight segment tags, which means email must handle Memorial Day tent promos only after education sends before Memorial Day sale week — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Mailchimp contributes familiar editor and broad marketing features. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Mailchimp reduced preview-time surprises because familiar editor and broad marketing features. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Allocation fear creates support tickets, not only unsubscribes. Board game pre-orders needed clear fulfillment-state emails; ambiguous cart recovery during allocation windows duplicated support load. State-aware automation paid for itself in Zendesk hours. For outdoor gear retailer specifically, merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day sale week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Mechanical Keyboard Vendor ($58k/mo) — halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed</h2>
        <p>
          The mechanical keyboard vendor does 940 orders/mo at roughly $58k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows six-week group-buy cycles on $180–$420 kits, which means email must handle GB close suppression and switch-type education across five PDPs before GB close deadlines — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Mailchimp contributes familiar editor and broad marketing features. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Mailchimp reduced preview-time surprises because familiar editor and broad marketing features. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Gift confusion is a December tax. Tea gift boxes and pottery starter sets both saw recipients hit unsubscribe when reorder emails assumed they were loyal drinkers or makers. Order property filters are not optional — they are deliverability insurance. For mechanical keyboard vendor specifically, halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise GB close deadlines becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Essen release week: board game store retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The board game store does 1,050 orders/mo at roughly $67k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows pre-order allocation anxiety on hot titles, which means email must handle pre-order state machines and fulfillment pivots after allocation closes before Essen release week — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Mailchimp contributes familiar editor and broad marketing features. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Yotpo Email & SMS reduced preview-time surprises because reviews. Mailchimp remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Inventory truth mattered as much as copy. When a limited run sold out mid-send, the tool that pulled live variant availability prevented angry clicks — the vinyl shop learned that on a 300-unit pressing that died during a two-hour send window. For board game store specifically, pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Essen release week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Specialty Tea Merchant: 28–35 day tin replenishment with gift-box seasonality</h2>
        <p>
          The specialty tea merchant does 720 orders/mo at roughly $44k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows 28–35 day tin replenishment with gift-box seasonality, which means email must handle subscription skip handling and gift-buyer exclusions in December before Q4 gift-box peak — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Mailchimp contributes familiar editor and broad marketing features. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Mailchimp reduced preview-time surprises because familiar editor and broad marketing features. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Allocation fear creates support tickets, not only unsubscribes. Board game pre-orders needed clear fulfillment-state emails; ambiguous cart recovery during allocation windows duplicated support load. State-aware automation paid for itself in Zendesk hours. For specialty tea merchant specifically, split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Q4 gift-box peak becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>How artisan coffee roaster emails through holiday blend drop</h2>
        <p>
          The artisan coffee roaster does 860 orders/mo at roughly $52k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows roast-date replenishment and wholesale sample follow-ups, which means email must handle bean reorder at day thirty with subscription pause confirmations before holiday blend drop — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Mailchimp contributes familiar editor and broad marketing features. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: suppress subscribers on pause from roast-date replenishment nudges.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Yotpo Email & SMS reduced preview-time surprises because reviews. Mailchimp remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mobile browse recovery front-runs cart on camping gear. Shoppers configured tents on phones during commute browsing; push or SMS reminders sometimes beat email when paired with disciplined suppression. Multichannel only helps with a collision doc. For artisan coffee roaster specifically, suppress subscribers on pause from roast-date replenishment nudges. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday blend drop becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Climbing Gear Store ($89k/mo) — branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages</h2>
        <p>
          The climbing gear store does 1,100 orders/mo at roughly $89k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows seven-to-fourteen day harness research cycles, which means email must handle certification education before percentage-off nudges on ropes before spring rack refresh — not after support tickets spike. Yotpo Email & SMS contributes reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite; Mailchimp contributes familiar editor and broad marketing features. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Mailchimp reduced preview-time surprises because familiar editor and broad marketing features. Yotpo Email & SMS remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          High-AOV safety content beats coupons. Climbing shoppers wanted retirement timelines and certification context; a 10% off rope email on day two would have trained worst practices. Education-first sequencing recovered more margin than blanket promos. For climbing gear store specifically, branch browse sequences by fall-rating and harness fit pages. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise spring rack refresh becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Tool friction where Yotpo Email & SMS and Mailchimp diverge on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Yotpo Email & SMS shines when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Its friction shows when you only need email without UGC or points. Mailchimp shines when broadcast muscle memory outweighs Shopify trigger depth. Its friction shows when cart and browse revenue attribution is load-bearing. Merchants that ignore friction points buy the wrong ceiling — or the wrong floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          Billing amplifies behavior. Yotpo Email & SMS (modular plans by product) rewards send discipline or punishes broadcast volume depending on your calendar. Mailchimp (contacts by tier) does the opposite in many stores. The vinyl shop imported thousands of waitlist emails while orders stayed flat; profile-style billing hurt. The outdoor retailer blasted engaged segments every May; send-weighted billing hurt. Model your real year, not a calm month.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reporting expectations differ. If your team opens lifecycle revenue reports every Monday, buy the tool that makes those reports trustworthy out of the box. If nobody reviews reports, buy for time-to-live and edit safety — not predictive metrics that become dashboard wallpaper.
        </p>
        <h2>Newsletter layer: editorial merchandising without discount training</h2>
        <p>
          Newsletters still matter. Coffee origin stories, vinyl staff picks, keyboard switch explainers, and climbing trip reports build trust before product blocks. Yotpo Email & SMS and Mailchimp both send product campaigns; the operational difference is how often you change hero SKUs mid-week and how live inventory syncs when a limited run sells out.
        </p>
        <p>
          Training customers to wait for codes is a hidden churn driver. If every Thursday email is twenty percent off, replenishment and winback lose meaning. Use editorial sends to teach grading, certification, player count, roast profiles, and tent capacity — then merchandise. Discipline beats platform.
        </p>
        <h2>Transactional-style moments and promo collision</h2>
        <p>
          Password resets belong on transactional infrastructure. Shipment delays, preorder timeline changes, and subscription skip confirmations can live in marketing ESPs only if copy and domain strategy separate operational tone from promos. Coffee brands on shared domains see complaint spikes when a roast release email resembles a receipt.
        </p>
        <p>
          Post-purchase cross-sells are where brands blur lines. An order update with three discount blocks reads promotional to filters when volume spikes. Document message categories before peak season. See <a class="link" href="/guides/deliverability">deliverability guide</a> for domain and reputation splitting.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing models that punish different mistakes</h2>
        <p>
          At 12,000–18,000 contacts, plans converge until they do not. Sunset cold imports before quoting either tool. Add SMS, push, reviews, or loyalty modules to the same spreadsheet — modular suites like Yotpo Email & SMS punish partial adoption.
        </p>
        <p>
          Project November, not February. Record Store Day, GB closes, Essen week, Memorial Day, and holiday gift-box peaks change send volume and support load. <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">Pricing models</a> helps build the year view.
        </p>
        <h2>Implementation workload and team shape</h2>
        <p>
          Integration is the easy hour. Exclusion logic, signup branching, gift properties, and sale-week edits are the long work. Budget two to four weeks for four journeys with DNS and forms. Never cut over during your highest-LTV catalog week.
        </p>
        <p>
          Match team shape to tool temperament. Solo founders bias toward time-to-live; retention operators bias toward holdout tests and browse depth. Agencies help either stack, but hours are a line item. See <a class="link" href="/guides/implementation-plan">implementation plan</a> for sequencing.
        </p>
        <h2>Five-job buyer test with scoring rubric</h2>
        <p>
          Score zero to two on: welcome by signup source; abandoned checkout with inventory check; post-purchase excluding gifts; replenishment with subscription suppression; winback split by discount sensitivity. Zero equals CSV exports. Two equals native edit before a drop. Paper-test both tools — demos lie.
        </p>
        <p>
          Time-to-live beats theoretical max when no retention engineer exists. A tea shop may accept ninety percent of maximum if ninety percent ships in one afternoon. A keyboard shop may need browse depth enough to wait two weeks for setup.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing scenario: 15,000 contacts, selective lifecycle sending</h2>
        <p>
          Picture 15,000 contacts, 1,400–2,200 orders monthly, 32,000–48,000 marketing emails in a normal month, higher in November and May. Profile billing charges for the full pool even when only engaged segments receive lifecycle mail. Send-weighted billing charges every broadcast you panic-send during a heatwave SKU miss.
        </p>
        <p>
          Holdout tests change ROI math. If winback discounts move customers who would reorder anyway, platform fees are not the expensive line — mis-measured incrementality is.
        </p>
        <h2>Migration sequencing and collision guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Export consent timestamps and suppressions. Rebuild welcome and cart first; parallel-monitor two weeks. Predictive segments, CRM pipelines, and push automations need explicit replacements — document what you are giving up. Pause legacy flows before enabling new ones.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hybrid stacks without priority docs duplicate cart recovery. If capture lives elsewhere, tag handoff must be explicit. See <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">flow collision prevention</a> before running two senders through sale week.
        </p>
        <h2>Measurement guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Separate replenishment from winback attribution. Tea and coffee merchants over-credit discount winback for natural consumption cycles. Hold out five percent of new subscribers on welcome tests. Measure incremental GMV with holdouts, not default dashboards.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multichannel requires one trigger-ownership spreadsheet reviewed before big sends. Tools do not replace ops discipline; some make violations easier to catch in preview.
        </p>
        <h2>Hybrid stack patterns on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Common pattern: capture in Privy or Justuno, lifecycle in Mailchimp, SMS in Postscript when compliance matters. Failure mode: three cart recovery senders with no priority order. Pick a primary lifecycle owner.
        </p>
        <p>
          Camping quiz capture fed education sequences while flash SMS handled weekend promos — with forty-five-minute suppression between cart channels. Collisions dropped before volume rose.
        </p>
        <h2>Who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Yotpo Email & SMS if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack</li>
          <li>You will use reviews, loyalty, email, and SMS in one retention suite weekly</li>
          <li>Modular plans by product fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Yotpo Email & SMS without external rescue</li>
          <li>Switching cost favors Yotpo Email & SMS for the next twelve months</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Mailchimp if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Broadcast muscle memory outweighs shopify trigger depth</li>
          <li>You will use familiar editor and broad marketing features weekly</li>
          <li>Contacts by tier fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Mailchimp without external rescue</li>
          <li>Incremental lifecycle GMV justifies Mailchimp migration</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Yotpo Email & SMS is the better Shopify email tool when reviews and loyalty already anchor your retention stack. Mailchimp is the better Shopify email tool when broadcast muscle memory outweighs Shopify trigger depth. Run the five-job buyer test in both UIs, model twelve-month billing with real sends and list hygiene, and pick whichever platform lets you edit audiences safely the Thursday before a drop — not whichever sales deck had the prettier logos. See <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">selection framework</a> and <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">pricing models</a> before annual contracts.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/omnisend-vs-mailchimp">Omnisend vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-mailchimp">Sequenzy vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/yotpo-email-sms-vs-omnisend">Yotpo vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/food-and-beverage">Email tools for food & beverage</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/welcome-series">Welcome series playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Yotpo Email & SMS vs Mailchimp FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
